[[File:Michinoomi no Mikoto.jpg|thumb|220px|Michinoomi no Mikoto / from ''Zenkō Kojitsu'']] [[File:Michinoomi no Mikoto following a crow to the enemy's lair LACMA M.2000.105.97.jpg|thumb|Illustration of Michinoomi no Mikoto in ''Dai Nippon Meishōkan'' by {{ill|Tsukioka Yoshitoshi|ja|月岡芳年|12=draft|12=draft}}]]
'''Michinoomi no Mikoto''' (道臣命) is a legendary figure from ancient [[Japan]], mentioned in the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}. Initially named '''Hinoomi no Mikoto''' (日臣命), he was a descendant of {{ill|Amenooshihi no Mikoto|ja|天忍日命|1=Ama-no-Oshihi|12=draft|12=draft}} and the ancestor of the {{ill|Ōtomo clan|ja|大伴氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. He served as a vanguard in {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}’s eastern campaign and later as a palace guard upon Emperor Jimmu’s accession.
== Achievements ==
During [[Jimmu's Eastern Expedition]], Michinoomi led the {{ill|Kumebe|ja|久米部|12=draft|12=draft}} warriors, guided by the divine {{ill|Yatagarasu|ja|八咫烏|12=draft|12=draft}}, to open a route from {{ill|Kumano|ja|熊野|12=draft|12=draft}} to Uda (modern {{ill|Uda|ja|宇陀|12=draft|12=draft}}). For his accomplishments, Emperor Jimmu bestowed upon him the name "Michinoomi."
When {{ill|Eukashi|ja|兄猾|12=draft|12=draft}} (Eukashi no Kami) attempted to ensnare Emperor Jimmu in a trap called "Oshi," Michinoomi confronted him, declaring, "Enter the house you built for yourself." With sword and bow ready, he forced Eukashi into his trap, where Eukashi perished. Michinoomi then dismembered Eukashi’s body, and the site became known as ''Chi-no-Hara'' (Blood Field) in Uda.
After the defeat of the {{ill|Eighty Bandit Chiefs|ja|八十梟帥|12=draft|12=draft}} at Kunimi-dake, Michinoomi was tasked with eradicating their remnants. He constructed a grand chamber in the village of Osaka and lured the bandits to a banquet. At the height of the feast, he signaled his troops with a {{ill|Kumebushi|ja|久米節|12=draft|12=draft}} war song, and they drew their swords to annihilate the enemy.
Earlier, Michinoomi had been appointed by Emperor Jimmu to serve as a priest for the worship of {{ill|Takamimusubi|ja|高皇産霊尊|12=draft|12=draft}}, earning the honorary title ''Izuhime'' (厳媛). Despite being male, this title reflects an ancient tradition of women officiating rituals.
Upon Emperor Jimmu’s enthronement, Michinoomi performed ceremonial songs and rituals to purify negative energies. In recognition of his service, he was granted a residence in ''Tsukisaka'' (present-day Kashihara, Nara Prefecture).
